his wealthy relations, would have &s;uffered him to
langui&s;h in ob&s;curity and di&s;tre&s;s; and, by turn|ing
his misfortune into reproach, made it a plea
for their own want of genero&s;ity and friend|&s;hip.</P>
<P>Peregrine, under&s;tanding this &s;ituation of his
friend's affairs, would have accommodated him,
