that if he would put him&s;elf under his di|rection,
he would return with them, and lay
&s;uch a &s;cheme, as would infallibly ruin the whole
&s;ociety at billiards, as he knew that Godfrey ex|celled
them all in his knowledge of that game.</P>
<P>The &s;oldier excu&s;ed him&s;elf from engaging in
any party of that kind; and after dinner the tra|vellers
<PB N="284" REF="293">
parted; but, as the conver&s;ation between
the two friends turned upon the information
they had received, Peregrine projected a plan for
puni&s;hing tho&s;e villanous pe&s;ts of &s;ociety, who
prey upon their fellow creatures; and it was put
